<ol>
  <li>Reduce the skewness of data using log,exponential, square root</li>
  <li>Skewness refers to the presence of outliers in the data stretching towards right or left of the normal distribution</li>
  <li>Kurtosis is the measure of sharpness of the peak of the normal distribution</li>
  <li>Use <strong>spatial sign</strong> for multiple predictors:</li>
</ol>

<h2 id="handling-outliers">Handling Outliers</h2>
<p><strong>Detection:</strong></p>

<ol>
  <li>Using z-score</li>
  <li>
    <p>Using box plots</p>

    <div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code> Q1 = np.percentile(data, 25, interpolation = 'midpoint')
 Q2 = np.percentile(data, 50, interpolation = 'midpoint')
 Q3 = np.percentile(data, 75, interpolation = 'midpoint')
 IQR = Q3-Q1
 Outlier = Q1 ‚Äì 1.5IQR and Q3 + 1.5QIQR
 print('Interquartile range is', IQR)
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
</ol>

<p><strong>Treatment</strong>:</p>

<ol>
  <li>Drop the outlier records</li>
  <li>Cap your outlier data</li>
  <li>Assign a new value</li>
  <li>Try a new transformation</li>
</ol>

<h2 id="encoding-categorical-variables">Encoding Categorical Variables</h2>
<ol>
  <li>
    <table>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>One hot encoding</strong>:  how to do it for large vectors? [How to Handle Categorical Features</td>
          <td>by Ashutosh Sahu</td>
          <td>Analytics Vidhya</td>
          <td>Medium](https://medium.com/analytics-vidhya/how-to-handle-categorical-features-ab65c3cf498e)</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </li>
  <li><strong>One hot encoding with Multiple Categories</strong>: In this technique, instead of creating the new column for every category, they limit creating the new column for 10 most frequent categories.</li>
  <li><strong>Ordinal Number Encoding:</strong> In this technique, each unique category value is given an integer value. For instance, ‚Äúred‚Äù equals 1, ‚Äúgreen‚Äù equals 2 and ‚Äúblue‚Äù equals 3.</li>
  <li><strong>Count or Frequency Encoding:</strong> In this technique we will substitute the categories by the count of the observations that show that category in the dataset</li>
  <li><strong>Target Guided Ordinal Encoding:</strong>
    <ol>
      <li>Choose a categorical variable.</li>
      <li>Take the aggregated mean of the categorical variable and apply it to the target variable.</li>
      <li>Assign higher integer values or a higher rank to the category with the highest mean.</li>
    </ol>
  </li>
  <li><strong>Mean Ordinal Encoding:</strong>¬†Replace the category with the obtained mean value instead of assigning integer values to it.</li>
  <li><strong>Probability Ratio Encoding:</strong> This technique is suitable for classification problems only when the target variable is binary(Either 1 or 0 or True or False). In this technique, we will substitute the category value with the probability ratio i.e. P(1)/P(0).
    <ol>
      <li>Using the categorical variable, evaluate the probability of the Target variable (where the output is True or 1).</li>
      <li>Calculate the probability of the Target variable having a False or 0 output.</li>
      <li>Calculate the probability ratio i.e. P(True or 1) / P(False or 0).</li>
      <li>Replace the category with a probability ratio.</li>
    </ol>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Weight of Evidence</strong> Explained later</p>
  </li>
  <li><strong>Label Encoding</strong></li>
</ol>

